To calculate the entropy of vaporization of chloroform at its normal boiling point, we can use the following equation:

\Delta S_{\text{vap}} = \frac{\Delta H_{\text{vap}}}{T_{\text{b}}}

where:
- \Delta S_{\text{vap}} is the entropy of vaporization
- \Delta H_{\text{vap}} is the enthalpy of vaporization
- T_{\text{b}} is the normal boiling point temperature

Given:
- \Delta H_{\text{vap}} = 29.4 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}
- T_{\text{b}} = 334.88 \mathrm{~K}

Step 1: Convert the enthalpy of vaporization from kJ/mol to J/mol.
\Delta H_{\text{vap}} = 29.4 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1} \times \frac{1000 \mathrm{~J}}{1 \mathrm{~kJ}} = 29400 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}

Step 2: Calculate the entropy of vaporization using the equation.
\Delta S_{\text{vap}} = \frac{\Delta H_{\text{vap}}}{T_{\text{b}}} = \frac{29400 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}}{334.88 \mathrm{~K}} = 87.76 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~K}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}

Therefore, the entropy of vaporization of chloroform at its normal boiling point is:

\boxed{87.76} \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~K}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}

