To calculate the Joule-Thomson coefficient, $\mu$, we can use the following formula:

\begin{equation*}
\mu = \left(\frac{\partial T}{\partial P}\right)_H
\end{equation*}

Given:
- Initial pressure, $P_1 = 32 \text{ atm}$
- Initial temperature, $T_1 = 0^\circ\text{C} = 273.15 \text{ K}$
- Final pressure, $P_2 = 1 \text{ atm}$
- Temperature change, $\Delta T = -22 \text{ K}$

Assuming $\mu$ remains constant over the temperature range, we can approximate it as:

\begin{equation*}
\mu \approx \frac{\Delta T}{\Delta P} = \frac{T_2 - T_1}{P_2 - P_1}
\end{equation*}

Substituting the given values:

\begin{equation*}
\mu \approx \frac{-22 \text{ K}}{1 \text{ atm} - 32 \text{ atm}} = \frac{-22}{-31} \text{ K atm}^{-1}
\end{equation*}

Simplifying the fraction:

\begin{equation*}
\mu \approx 0.7097 \text{ K atm}^{-1}
\end{equation*}

Therefore, the Joule-Thomson coefficient at $0^\circ\text{C}$ is:

\begin{equation*}
\boxed{0.7097} \text{ K atm}^{-1}
\end{equation*}

