To find the molar heat capacity at constant pressure, we can use the formula:

\begin{align*}
q &= nC_p\Delta T\\
\Rightarrow C_p &= \frac{q}{n\Delta T}
\end{align*}

where $q$ is the heat supplied, $n$ is the number of moles, $\Delta T$ is the change in temperature, and $C_p$ is the molar heat capacity at constant pressure.

Given:
$q = 229 \mathrm{~J}$
$n = 3.0 \mathrm{~mol}$
$\Delta T = 2.55 \mathrm{~K}$

Substituting the given values:

\begin{align*}
C_p &= \frac{229 \mathrm{~J}}{(3.0 \mathrm{~mol})(2.55 \mathrm{~K})}\\
&= \frac{229}{7.65} \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~K}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}\\
&= 29.93 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~K}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the molar heat capacity at constant pressure of the gas is:

\boxed{29.93} $\mathrm{J} \mathrm{K}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$

