To calculate the standard enthalpy of combustion of ethylbenzene, we need to consider the balanced chemical equation for the combustion reaction:

\ce{C8H10 + 21/2 O2 -> 8 CO2 + 5 H2O}

The standard enthalpy of combustion is the sum of the standard enthalpies of formation of the products minus the sum of the standard enthalpies of formation of the reactants.

\Delta H_{\text{comb}}^{\circ} = \left[8 \Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}(\text{CO}_2) + 5 \Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}(\text{H}_2\text{O})\right] - \left[\Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}(\text{C}_8\text{H}_{10}) + \frac{21}{2} \Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}(\text{O}_2)\right]

Given:
\Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}(\text{C}_8\text{H}_{10}) = -12.5 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}
\Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}(\text{CO}_2) = -393.5 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}
\Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}(\text{H}_2\text{O}) = -285.8 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}
\Delta H_{\text{f}}^{\circ}(\text{O}_2) = 0 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1} (by definition for an element in its standard state)

Substituting the values:

\Delta H_{\text{comb}}^{\circ} = \left[8(-393.5) + 5(-285.8)\right] - \left[(-12.5) + \frac{21}{2}(0)\right]
\Delta H_{\text{comb}}^{\circ} = (-3148 - 1429) - (-12.5)
\Delta H_{\text{comb}}^{\circ} = -4574.5 + 12.5
\Delta H_{\text{comb}}^{\circ} = -4562 \mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}

Therefore, the standard enthalpy of combustion of ethylbenzene is:

\boxed{-4562}\mathrm{~kJ} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}

