To calculate the Gibbs energy of mixing, we use the following formula:

\begin{equation*}
\Delta G_{\text{mix}} = -T \Delta S_{\text{mix}}
\end{equation*}

where $T$ is the temperature in Kelvin and $\Delta S_{\text{mix}}$ is the entropy change upon mixing.

First, convert the temperature from Celsius to Kelvin:
\begin{equation*}
T = 25^{\circ} \mathrm{C} + 273.15 = 298.15 \mathrm{~K}
\end{equation*}

Next, calculate the entropy change upon mixing using the formula:
\begin{equation*}
\Delta S_{\text{mix}} = -n R \sum_{i} x_i \ln x_i
\end{equation*}

where $n$ is the total number of moles, $R$ is the gas constant ($8.314 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~K}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$), and $x_i$ is the mole fraction of each gas.

The total number of moles is:
\begin{equation*}
n = 3.0 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{H}_2 + 1.0 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{N}_2 = 4.0 \mathrm{~mol}
\end{equation*}

The mole fractions are:
\begin{equation*}
x_{\mathrm{H}_2} = \frac{3.0 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{H}_2}{4.0 \mathrm{~mol}} = 0.75
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
x_{\mathrm{N}_2} = \frac{1.0 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{N}_2}{4.0 \mathrm{~mol}} = 0.25
\end{equation*}

Now, calculate the entropy change:
\begin{align*}
\Delta S_{\text{mix}} &= -n R \sum_{i} x_i \ln x_i \\
&= -(4.0 \mathrm{~mol}) (8.314 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~K}^{-1} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}) (0.75 \ln 0.75 + 0.25 \ln 0.25) \\
&= 19.14 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}
\end{align*}

Finally, calculate the Gibbs energy of mixing:
\begin{align*}
\Delta G_{\text{mix}} &= -T \Delta S_{\text{mix}} \\
&= -(298.15 \mathrm{~K}) (19.14 \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~K}^{-1}) \\
&= -5708.49 \mathrm{~J} \\
&= -5.71 \mathrm{~kJ}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the Gibbs energy of mixing when the partition is removed is:
\begin{equation*}
\boxed{-5.71} \mathrm{~kJ}
\end{equation*}

