To calculate the reduced mass of a nitrogen molecule, we can use the following formula:

\begin{equation*}
\mu = \frac{m_1 m_2}{m_1 + m_2}
\end{equation*}

where $\mu$ is the reduced mass, and $m_1$ and $m_2$ are the masses of the two nitrogen atoms.

Given that both nitrogen atoms have an atomic mass of 14.00, we can substitute these values into the formula:

\begin{align*}
\mu &= \frac{14.00 \times 14.00}{14.00 + 14.00} \\
&= \frac{196.00}{28.00} \\
&= 7.00
\end{align*}

Therefore, the reduced mass of the nitrogen molecule is:

\begin{equation*}
\boxed{7.00}\,\text{amu}
\end{equation*}

