To calculate the de Broglie wavelength of an electron traveling at $1.00\%$ of the speed of light, we need to use the de Broglie wavelength formula:

\begin{equation*}
\lambda = \frac{h}{mv}
\end{equation*}

where $\lambda$ is the de Broglie wavelength, $h$ is Planck's constant, $m$ is the mass of the electron, and $v$ is the velocity of the electron.

Given:
- $v = 1.00\%$ of the speed of light $= 0.01 \times 2.998 \times 10^8 \, \mathrm{m/s} = 2.998 \times 10^6 \, \mathrm{m/s}$
- $h = 6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \mathrm{J \cdot s}$
- $m = 9.109 \times 10^{-31} \, \mathrm{kg}$

Step 1: Substitute the given values into the de Broglie wavelength formula.

\begin{align*}
\lambda &= \frac{h}{mv} \\
&= \frac{6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \mathrm{J \cdot s}}{(9.109 \times 10^{-31} \, \mathrm{kg}) \times (2.998 \times 10^6 \, \mathrm{m/s})}
\end{align*}

Step 2: Simplify the expression.

\begin{align*}
\lambda &= \frac{6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \mathrm{J \cdot s}}{(9.109 \times 10^{-31} \, \mathrm{kg}) \times (2.998 \times 10^6 \, \mathrm{m/s})} \\
&= \frac{6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \mathrm{kg \cdot m^2/s}}{(9.109 \times 10^{-31} \, \mathrm{kg}) \times (2.998 \times 10^6 \, \mathrm{m/s})} \\
&= \frac{6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \mathrm{m}}{9.109 \times 10^{-31} \times 2.998 \times 10^6} \\
&= \frac{6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \mathrm{m}}{2.730 \times 10^{-24}} \\
&= 2.426 \times 10^{-10} \, \mathrm{m}
\end{align*}

Step 3: Convert the wavelength from meters to picometers.

\begin{align*}
\lambda &= 2.426 \times 10^{-10} \, \mathrm{m} \times \frac{10^{12} \, \mathrm{pm}}{1 \, \mathrm{m}} \\
&= 242.6 \, \mathrm{pm}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the de Broglie wavelength of an electron traveling at $1.00\%$ of the speed of light is:

\begin{equation*}
\boxed{242.6}\,\mathrm{pm}
\end{equation*}

