To calculate the energy of one mole of UV photons, we will use the following steps:

1. Convert the wavelength from $\mathrm{nm}$ to $\mathrm{m}$.
2. Calculate the energy of a single photon using the Planck's equation.
3. Calculate the energy of one mole of photons.
4. Compare the energy with a typical single-bond energy.

Step 1: Convert the wavelength from $\mathrm{nm}$ to $\mathrm{m}$.
\begin{align*}
\lambda &= 300 \mathrm{~nm} \\
&= 300 \times 10^{-9} \mathrm{~m} \\
&= 3 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~m}
\end{align*}

Step 2: Calculate the energy of a single photon using the Planck's equation.
\begin{align*}
E_{\text{photon}} &= h \nu = \frac{h c}{\lambda} \\
&= \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \mathrm{~J} \cdot \mathrm{s})(2.998 \times 10^8 \mathrm{~m}/\mathrm{s})}{3 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~m}} \\
&= 6.626 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{~J}
\end{align*}

Step 3: Calculate the energy of one mole of photons.
\begin{align*}
E_{\text{mole}} &= E_{\text{photon}} \times N_A \\
&= (6.626 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{~J}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}) \\
&= 399000 \mathrm{~J}/\mathrm{mol} \\
&= 399 \mathrm{~kJ}/\mathrm{mol}
\end{align*}

Step 4: Compare the energy with a typical single-bond energy.
\begin{align*}
\text{Energy ratio} &= \frac{E_{\text{mole}}}{E_{\text{bond}}} \\
&= \frac{399 \mathrm{~kJ}/\mathrm{mol}}{400 \mathrm{~kJ}/\mathrm{mol}} \\
&= 0.998
\end{align*}

Therefore, the energy of one mole of UV photons is \boxed{399} $\mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$, which is comparable to the typical single-bond energy of $400 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$.

