To calculate the magnitude of the spin magnetic moment of an electron, we use the following formula:

\begin{align*}
\mu &= g_s \mu_B \sqrt{s(s+1)} \\
\end{align*}

where:
- $\mu$ is the spin magnetic moment
- $g_s$ is the electron spin g-factor (approximately 2.0023)
- $\mu_B$ is the Bohr magneton (approximately $9.274 \times 10^{-24} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{T}$)
- $s$ is the electron spin quantum number (1/2 for an electron)

Substituting the values:

\begin{align*}
\mu &= 2.0023 \times (9.274 \times 10^{-24} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{T}) \times \sqrt{\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{2}+1\right)} \\
&= 2.0023 \times (9.274 \times 10^{-24} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{T}) \times \sqrt{\frac{3}{4}} \\
&= 2.0023 \times (9.274 \times 10^{-24} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{T}) \times \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \\
&\approx 9.284 \times 10^{-24} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{T}
\end{align*}

Converting the unit to $10^{-23} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{T}$:

\begin{align*}
\mu &\approx 0.9284 \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{T}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the magnitude of the spin magnetic moment of an electron is:

\boxed{0.9284} \times 10^{-23} \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{T}

