To calculate the equilibrium polarization of 13C nuclei in a 20.0 T magnetic field at 300 K, we need to use the Boltzmann distribution. The polarization is given by the following equation:

\begin{equation*}
P = \frac{n_\uparrow - n_\downarrow}{n_\uparrow + n_\downarrow}
\end{equation*}

where $n_\uparrow$ and $n_\downarrow$ are the populations of the spin-up and spin-down states, respectively. According to the Boltzmann distribution:

\begin{equation*}
\frac{n_\uparrow}{n_\downarrow} = e^{-\frac{\Delta E}{kT}}
\end{equation*}

where $\Delta E$ is the energy difference between the two states, $k$ is the Boltzmann constant, and $T$ is the temperature. The energy difference is given by:

\begin{equation*}
\Delta E = \gamma \hbar B_0
\end{equation*}

where $\gamma$ is the gyromagnetic ratio of 13C, $\hbar$ is the reduced Planck constant, and $B_0$ is the magnetic field strength. The gyromagnetic ratio of 13C is $6.728 \times 10^7$ rad/s/T. Substituting the values, we get:

\begin{align*}
\Delta E &= (6.728 \times 10^7 \text{ rad/s/T}) \times (1.055 \times 10^{-34} \text{ J s}) \times (20.0 \text{ T}) \\
&= 1.415 \times 10^{-26} \text{ J}
\end{align*}

Now, we can calculate the ratio of the populations:

\begin{align*}
\frac{n_\uparrow}{n_\downarrow} &= e^{-\frac{1.415 \times 10^{-26} \text{ J}}{(1.381 \times 10^{-23} \text{ J/K}) \times (300 \text{ K})}} \\
&= e^{-0.0003412} \\
&= 0.9996588
\end{align*}

Finally, we can calculate the polarization:

\begin{align*}
P &= \frac{n_\uparrow - n_\downarrow}{n_\uparrow + n_\downarrow} \\
&= \frac{0.9996588 - 1}{0.9996588 + 1} \\
&= \frac{-0.0003412}{1.9996588} \\
&= -0.0001706
\end{align*}

Therefore, the equilibrium polarization of 13C nuclei in a 20.0 T magnetic field at 300 K is:

\begin{equation*}
\boxed{-0.0001706}
\end{equation*}

