To calculate the lower resonant field position, we can use the following equation:

\begin{equation*}
B_{res} = \frac{h\nu}{g\beta} - \frac{A}{2}
\end{equation*}

where:
- $B_{res}$ is the resonant field position,
- $h$ is the Planck's constant ($6.626 \times 10^{-34}$ Js),
- $\nu$ is the microwave frequency (9.5 GHz),
- $g$ is the g-factor (2.005),
- $\beta$ is the Bohr magneton ($9.274 \times 10^{-24}$ J/T),
- $A$ is the hyperfine coupling constant (280 MHz).

First, convert the microwave frequency from GHz to Hz:
\begin{equation*}
\nu = 9.5 \times 10^9 \text{ Hz}
\end{equation*}

Next, convert the hyperfine coupling constant from MHz to Hz:
\begin{equation*}
A = 280 \times 10^6 \text{ Hz}
\end{equation*}

Now, calculate the lower resonant field position:
\begin{align*}
B_{res} &= \frac{h\nu}{g\beta} - \frac{A}{2} \\
&= \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \text{ Js})(9.5 \times 10^9 \text{ Hz})}{(2.005)(9.274 \times 10^{-24} \text{ J/T})} - \frac{280 \times 10^6 \text{ Hz}}{2} \\
&= 0.03402 \text{ T}
\end{align*}

Convert the resonant field position from T to mT:
\begin{equation*}
B_{res} = 0.03402 \text{ T} \times 1000 = 34.02 \text{ mT}
\end{equation*}

Therefore, the lower resonant field position is:
\begin{equation*}
\boxed{34.02}\text{ mT}
\end{equation*}

