To find the difference in activation free energies, we can use the Eyring equation:

\begin{align*}
\Delta G^{\ddagger} = -RT \ln \left( \frac{k}{k_B T} \right)
\end{align*}

where \( \Delta G^{\ddagger} \) is the activation free energy, \( R \) is the gas constant (8.314 J/mol·K), \( T \) is the temperature in Kelvin (298 K), \( k \) is the rate constant, and \( k_B \) is the Boltzmann constant (1.38 × 10⁻²³ J/K).

First, let's calculate the activation free energy for the catalyzed reaction:

\begin{align*}
\Delta G^{\ddagger}_{\text{cat}} &= -RT \ln \left( \frac{k_{\text{cat}}}{k_B T} \right) \\
&= - (8.314 \text{ J/mol·K}) (298 \text{ K}) \ln \left( \frac{14 \text{ s}^{-1}}{(1.38 \times 10^{-23} \text{ J/K}) (298 \text{ K})} \right) \\
&= -24540.84 \text{ J/mol}
\end{align*}

Now, let's calculate the activation free energy for the uncatalyzed reaction:

\begin{align*}
\Delta G^{\ddagger}_{\text{uncat}} &= -RT \ln \left( \frac{k_{\text{uncat}}}{k_B T} \right) \\
&= - (8.314 \text{ J/mol·K}) (298 \text{ K}) \ln \left( \frac{1 \times 10^{-15} \text{ s}^{-1}}{(1.38 \times 10^{-23} \text{ J/K}) (298 \text{ K})} \right) \\
&= -126000.72 \text{ J/mol}
\end{align*}

The difference in activation free energies is:

\begin{align*}
\Delta \Delta G^{\ddagger} &= \Delta G^{\ddagger}_{\text{uncat}} - \Delta G^{\ddagger}_{\text{cat}} \\
&= -126000.72 \text{ J/mol} - (-24540.84 \text{ J/mol}) \\
&= -101459.88 \text{ J/mol}
\end{align*}

Converting to kJ/mol:

\begin{align*}
\Delta \Delta G^{\ddagger} &= -101.46 \text{ kJ/mol}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the difference in the activation free energies of these two reactions is \boxed{-101.46} kJ/mol.

