To calculate the normal sublimation temperature of solid iodine, we can use the Clausius-Clapeyron equation:

\begin{equation*}
\ln\left(\frac{P_{2}}{P_{1}}\right) = \frac{\Delta_{\text{sub}}H_{m}}{R} \left(\frac{1}{T_{1}} - \frac{1}{T_{2}}\right)
\end{equation*}

where \(P_{1}\) and \(P_{2}\) are the vapor pressures at temperatures \(T_{1}\) and \(T_{2}\), respectively, \(\Delta_{\text{sub}}H_{m}\) is the molar enthalpy of sublimation, and \(R\) is the ideal gas constant (8.314 J¡¤mol\(^{-1}\)¡¤K\(^{-1}\)).

At the normal sublimation temperature, the vapor pressure of solid iodine equals 1 atm (101.325 kPa). We can assume that the vapor pressure at room temperature (298 K) is negligible compared to 1 atm. Therefore, we can simplify the equation:

\begin{equation*}
\ln\left(\frac{1}{0}\right) = \frac{\Delta_{\text{sub}}H_{m}}{R} \left(\frac{1}{T_{1}} - \frac{1}{T_{\text{sub}}}\right)
\end{equation*}

To find \(\Delta_{\text{sub}}H_{m}\), we can use the relationship between the standard molar enthalpy of formation and the standard molar entropies:

\begin{equation*}
\Delta_{\text{sub}}H_{m} = \Delta_{f}H_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(g)}) - \Delta_{f}H_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(s)})
\end{equation*}

Since \(\Delta_{f}H_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(s)}) = 0\) (by definition for elements in their standard state):

\begin{equation*}
\Delta_{\text{sub}}H_{m} = 62.4\ \text{kJ¡¤mol}^{-1} = 62400\ \text{J¡¤mol}^{-1}
\end{equation*}

Now, we can use the relationship between the standard molar entropies and the molar enthalpy of sublimation:

\begin{equation*}
\Delta_{\text{sub}}S_{m} = \frac{\Delta_{\text{sub}}H_{m}}{T_{\text{sub}}}
\end{equation*}

\begin{equation*}
\Delta_{\text{sub}}S_{m} = S_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(g)}) - S_{m}^{\ominus}(\ce{I_{2}(s)}) = 260.7 - 116.1 = 144.6\ \text{J¡¤mol}^{-1}¡¤\text{K}^{-1}
\end{equation*}

Solving for \(T_{\text{sub}}\):

\begin{equation*}
T_{\text{sub}} = \frac{\Delta_{\text{sub}}H_{m}}{\Delta_{\text{sub}}S_{m}} = \frac{62400}{144.6} \approx 431.6\ \text{K}
\end{equation*}

Therefore, the normal sublimation temperature of solid iodine is:

\begin{equation*}
\boxed{431.6}\ \text{K}
\end{equation*}

