To solve this problem, we will use Hess's Law, which states that the total enthalpy change for a reaction is the sum of the enthalpy changes for each step in the reaction, regardless of the order of the steps. We can use the given enthalpy changes of formation to calculate the enthalpy change for the desired reaction.

First, let's write down the given enthalpy changes of formation:
\begin{align*}
\Delta H_f^\circ(\ce{CH4(g)}) &= \pu{-74.8 kJ mol^{-1}} \\
\Delta H_f^\circ(\ce{CO2(g)}) &= \pu{-393.5 kJ mol^{-1}} \\
\Delta H_f^\circ(\ce{H2O(l)}) &= \pu{-285.8 kJ mol^{-1}}
\end{align*}

The desired reaction is:
\begin{align*}
\ce{CH4(g) + 2H2O(l) -> CO2(g) + 4H2(g)}
\end{align*}

To calculate the enthalpy change for this reaction, we can use the following equation:
\begin{align*}
\Delta H_{\text{rxn}} = \sum \Delta H_f^\circ(\text{products}) - \sum \Delta H_f^\circ(\text{reactants})
\end{align*}

Substituting the given values:
\begin{align*}
\Delta H_{\text{rxn}} &= \left[1 \cdot \Delta H_f^\circ(\ce{CO2(g)}) + 4 \cdot \Delta H_f^\circ(\ce{H2(g)})\right] - \left[1 \cdot \Delta H_f^\circ(\ce{CH4(g)}) + 2 \cdot \Delta H_f^\circ(\ce{H2O(l)})\right] \\
&= \left[1 \cdot (\pu{-393.5 kJ mol^{-1}}) + 4 \cdot 0\right] - \left[1 \cdot (\pu{-74.8 kJ mol^{-1}}) + 2 \cdot (\pu{-285.8 kJ mol^{-1}})\right] \\
&= (\pu{-393.5 kJ mol^{-1}}) - (\pu{-74.8 kJ mol^{-1}} + \pu{-571.6 kJ mol^{-1}}) \\
&= \pu{-393.5 kJ mol^{-1}} - (\pu{-646.4 kJ mol^{-1}}) \\
&= \pu{252.9 kJ mol^{-1}}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the enthalpy change for the reaction \ce{CH4(g) + 2H2O(l) -> CO2(g) + 4H2(g)} is:
\begin{align*}
\boxed{252.9} \, \pu{kJ mol^{-1}}
\end{align*}

