\ce{2H2O(l) -> 2H2(g) + O2(g)}

Step 2: Calculate the enthalpy change for the formation of 2 moles of \ce{H2O(l)}.
\Delta H_{\text{formation}} = 2 \times (-285.8 \text{ kJ mol}^{-1}) = -571.6 \text{ kJ mol}^{-1}

Step 3: The enthalpy change for the electrolysis of water is the reverse of the enthalpy change for the formation of water. Therefore, the enthalpy change for the electrolysis of water is the negative of the enthalpy change for the formation of 2 moles of \ce{H2O(l)}.
\Delta H_{\text{electrolysis}} = -\Delta H_{\text{formation}} = 571.6 \text{ kJ mol}^{-1}

Final answer:
\boxed{571.6} \text{ kJ mol}^{-1}

