To solve this problem, we need to find the number of moles of gas produced by the explosion of TNT and then calculate the mass of TNT required to produce that amount of gas.

1. Determine the total moles of gas produced by the reaction:
   \begin{align*}
   \text{Total moles of gas} &= 3 \text{ moles CO} + 1 \text{ mole CO}_2 + 1.5 \text{ moles H}_2 + 1.5 \text{ moles N}_2 + 1 \text{ mole H}_2\text{O} \\
   &= 3 + 1 + 1.5 + 1.5 + 1 = 8 \text{ moles}
   \end{align*}

2. Calculate the number of moles of gas in \pu{1.0 dm^{3}} at RTP:
   \begin{align*}
   \text{Moles of gas in 1.0 dm}^3 &= \frac{\text{Volume of gas}}{\text{Molar volume at RTP}} \\
   &= \frac{1.0 \text{ dm}^3}{24 \text{ dm}^3/\text{mol}} = \frac{1}{24} \text{ moles}
   \end{align*}

3. Determine the fraction of the total moles of gas that \pu{1.0 dm^{3}} represents:
   \begin{align*}
   \text{Fraction of total moles} &= \frac{\text{Moles of gas in 1.0 dm}^3}{\text{Total moles of gas}} \\
   &= \frac{1/24}{8} = \frac{1}{192}
   \end{align*}

4. Calculate the molar mass of TNT (\ce{C7H5N3O6}):
   \begin{align*}
   \text{Molar mass of TNT} &= 7 \times 12.01 \text{ g/mol (C)} + 5 \times 1.01 \text{ g/mol (H)} + 3 \times 14.01 \text{ g/mol (N)} + 6 \times 16.00 \text{ g/mol (O)} \\
   &= 227.13 \text{ g/mol}
   \end{align*}

5. Calculate the mass of TNT required to produce \pu{1.0 dm^{3}} of gas:
   \begin{align*}
   \text{Mass of TNT} &= \text{Fraction of total moles} \times \text{Molar mass of TNT} \\
   &= \frac{1}{192} \times 227.13 \text{ g/mol} \\
   &= 1.182 \text{ g}
   \end{align*}

Therefore, the mass of TNT required to produce \pu{1.0 dm^{3}} of gas at room temperature and pressure is \boxed{1.182}~\pu{g}.

