To solve this problem, we need to consider the following steps:

1. Calculate the initial concentration of hydrogen ions in the blood.
2. Calculate the concentration of hydrogen ions after the pH change.
3. Determine the moles of hydrogen ions added to the solution.
4. Calculate the moles of lactic acid added to the solution.

Step 1: Calculate the initial concentration of hydrogen ions in the blood.
Given the initial pH of 7.40, we can calculate the initial concentration of hydrogen ions using the formula:
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{pH} &= -\log[\mathrm{H}^+] \\
7.40 &= -\log[\mathrm{H}^+]_i \\
[\mathrm{H}^+]_i &= 10^{-7.40} \\
[\mathrm{H}^+]_i &= 3.981 \times 10^{-8} \, \mathrm{M}
\end{align*}

Step 2: Calculate the concentration of hydrogen ions after the pH change.
Given the final pH of 7.00, we can calculate the final concentration of hydrogen ions using the same formula:
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{pH} &= -\log[\mathrm{H}^+] \\
7.00 &= -\log[\mathrm{H}^+]_f \\
[\mathrm{H}^+]_f &= 10^{-7.00} \\
[\mathrm{H}^+]_f &= 1.000 \times 10^{-7} \, \mathrm{M}
\end{align*}

Step 3: Determine the moles of hydrogen ions added to the solution.
The moles of hydrogen ions added to the solution can be calculated using the difference between the final and initial concentrations of hydrogen ions:
\begin{align*}
\Delta[\mathrm{H}^+] &= [\mathrm{H}^+]_f - [\mathrm{H}^+]_i \\
\Delta[\mathrm{H}^+] &= (1.000 \times 10^{-7} - 3.981 \times 10^{-8}) \, \mathrm{M} \\
\Delta[\mathrm{H}^+] &= 6.019 \times 10^{-8} \, \mathrm{M}
\end{align*}
Since the volume of the solution is 1.00 dm³, the moles of hydrogen ions added is equal to the change in concentration:
\begin{align*}
\Delta n(\mathrm{H}^+) &= \Delta[\mathrm{H}^+] \times V \\
\Delta n(\mathrm{H}^+) &= 6.019 \times 10^{-8} \, \mathrm{mol}
\end{align*}

Step 4: Calculate the moles of lactic acid added to the solution.
Lactic acid (HL) is a monoprotic acid, meaning it donates one hydrogen ion per molecule when it dissociates. Therefore, the moles of lactic acid added to the solution is equal to the moles of hydrogen ions added:
\begin{align*}
\Delta n(\mathrm{HL}) &= \Delta n(\mathrm{H}^+) \\
\Delta n(\mathrm{HL}) &= 6.019 \times 10^{-8} \, \mathrm{mol}
\end{align*}

Thus, the final answer is:
\boxed{6.019e-08} \, \mathrm{mol}

