To solve this problem, we need to determine the concentration of chloride ions in the bay water sample. We will use the data from the Volhard method titration.

Given:
- Volume of bay water sample: $50.00 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$
- Concentration of $\mathrm{AgNO}_{3}$ solution: $0.00129 \mathrm{M}$
- Volume of $\mathrm{AgNO}_{3}$ solution added: $50.00 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$
- Concentration of KSCN solution: $1.4110^{-3} \mathrm{M}$
- Volume of KSCN solution used for titration: $27.46 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}$

Step 1: Calculate the moles of excess $\mathrm{Ag}^{+}$ ions.
\begin{align*}
\text{Moles of excess } \mathrm{Ag}^{+} &= \text{Volume of KSCN} \times \text{Concentration of KSCN} \\
&= 27.46 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \times 1.4110^{-3} \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{dm}^{-3} \\
&= 0.0387 \mathrm{~mmol}
\end{align*}

Step 2: Calculate the total moles of $\mathrm{Ag}^{+}$ ions added to the sample.
\begin{align*}
\text{Total moles of } \mathrm{Ag}^{+} &= \text{Volume of } \mathrm{AgNO}_{3} \times \text{Concentration of } \mathrm{AgNO}_{3} \\
&= 50.00 \mathrm{~cm}^{3} \times 0.00129 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{dm}^{-3} \\
&= 0.0645 \mathrm{~mmol}
\end{align*}

Step 3: Calculate the moles of $\mathrm{Ag}^{+}$ ions reacted with $\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$ ions.
\begin{align*}
\text{Moles of } \mathrm{Ag}^{+} \text{ reacted with } \mathrm{Cl}^{-} &= \text{Total moles of } \mathrm{Ag}^{+} - \text{Moles of excess } \mathrm{Ag}^{+} \\
&= 0.0645 \mathrm{~mmol} - 0.0387 \mathrm{~mmol} \\
&= 0.0258 \mathrm{~mmol}
\end{align*}

Step 4: Calculate the concentration of $\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$ ions in the bay water sample.
\begin{align*}
\text{Concentration of } \mathrm{Cl}^{-} &= \frac{\text{Moles of } \mathrm{Ag}^{+} \text{ reacted with } \mathrm{Cl}^{-}}{\text{Volume of bay water sample}} \\
&= \frac{0.0258 \mathrm{~mmol}}{50.00 \mathrm{~cm}^{3}} \\
&= 0.000516 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{dm}^{-3}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the concentration of chloride ions in the bay water sample is \boxed{0.000516} $\mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{dm}^{-3}$.

