To solve this problem, we will use the concept of stoichiometry and the balanced chemical equation for the reaction between HCl and $\ce{Ba(OH)_2}$. The balanced equation is:

$\ce{2HCl + Ba(OH)_2 -> BaCl_2 + 2H_2O}$

From the balanced equation, we can see that 2 moles of HCl react with 1 mole of $\ce{Ba(OH)_2}$. 

Step 1: Calculate the moles of $\ce{Ba(OH)_2}$ used in the titration.
\begin{align*}
\text{moles of } \ce{Ba(OH)_2} &= \text{volume of } \ce{Ba(OH)_2} \times \text{molarity of } \ce{Ba(OH)_2} \\
&= 29.71 \text{ mL} \times 0.01963 \text{ M} \\
&= 0.5833 \text{ mmol}
\end{align*}

Step 2: Use the stoichiometry of the reaction to find the moles of HCl.
\begin{align*}
\text{moles of HCl} &= 2 \times \text{moles of } \ce{Ba(OH)_2} \\
&= 2 \times 0.5833 \text{ mmol} \\
&= 1.1666 \text{ mmol}
\end{align*}

Step 3: Calculate the molar concentration of HCl.
\begin{align*}
\text{molarity of HCl} &= \frac{\text{moles of HCl}}{\text{volume of HCl}} \\
&= \frac{1.1666 \text{ mmol}}{50.00 \text{ mL}} \\
&= 0.02333 \text{ M}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the molar concentration of the HCl solution is \boxed{0.02333} M.

