To calculate the rotational contributions to the molar Gibbs energy at 298 K, we need to use the following equation:

\begin{equation*}
G_{\text{rot}} = -RT \ln \left( \frac{kT}{\sigma h c B} \right)
\end{equation*}

where:
- $G_{\text{rot}}$ is the rotational contribution to the molar Gibbs energy,
- $R$ is the gas constant (8.3145 J mol$^{-1}$ K$^{-1}$),
- $T$ is the temperature (298 K),
- $k$ is the Boltzmann constant (1.3807 $\times$ 10$^{-23}$ J K$^{-1}$),
- $\sigma$ is the symmetry number (2 for a linear molecule like CO$_2$),
- $h$ is the Planck constant (6.6261 $\times$ 10$^{-34}$ Js),
- $c$ is the speed of light (2.9979 $\times$ 10$^{10}$ cm s$^{-1}$),
- $B$ is the rotational constant (0.3902 cm$^{-1}$).

First, let's calculate the value inside the logarithm:

\begin{align*}
\frac{kT}{\sigma h c B} &= \frac{(1.3807 \times 10^{-23} \text{ J K}^{-1}) \times (298 \text{ K})}{2 \times (6.6261 \times 10^{-34} \text{ Js}) \times (2.9979 \times 10^{10} \text{ cm s}^{-1}) \times (0.3902 \text{ cm}^{-1})} \\
&= 212.87
\end{align*}

Now, we can calculate the rotational contribution to the molar Gibbs energy:

\begin{align*}
G_{\text{rot}} &= -RT \ln \left( \frac{kT}{\sigma h c B} \right) \\
&= -(8.3145 \text{ J mol}^{-1} \text{ K}^{-1}) \times (298 \text{ K}) \times \ln(212.87) \\
&= -17270.5 \text{ J mol}^{-1}
\end{align*}

Converting the answer to kJ mol$^{-1}$:

\begin{align*}
G_{\text{rot}} &= -17.27 \text{ kJ mol}^{-1}
\end{align*}

Therefore, the rotational contribution to the molar Gibbs energy at 298 K is:

\begin{equation*}
\boxed{-17.27} \text{ kJ mol}^{-1}
\end{equation*}

