To determine the pressure of the nitrogen gas using the van der Waals equation, we need to follow these steps:

1. Convert the volume from m³ to dm³.
2. Calculate the number of moles of nitrogen.
3. Apply the van der Waals equation to find the pressure.

Step 1: Convert the volume from m³ to dm³
\begin{align*}
V &= 1.000\ \text{m}^3 \times \left(\frac{1000\ \text{dm}}{1\ \text{m}}\right)^3 \\
&= 1000\ \text{dm}^3
\end{align*}

Step 2: Calculate the number of moles of nitrogen
\begin{align*}
n &= \frac{m}{M} \\
&= \frac{92.4\ \text{kg}}{28.014\ \text{g/mol} \times \frac{1\ \text{kg}}{1000\ \text{g}}} \\
&= \frac{92.4 \times 1000}{28.014} \\
&= 3301.99\ \text{mol}
\end{align*}

Step 3: Apply the van der Waals equation to find the pressure
The van der Waals equation is given by:
